Welcome to notebook twelve of the Java track. This is the final notebook. The topic for this session is Spring Cloud. The previous notebook gave us a single production grade Spring service. This notebook turns that one service into one node of a distributed system, with many services, many machines, and many runtime concerns that simply do not exist when everything fits in one process.

Here is the map for what we will cover. First, why Spring Cloud exists and what changes when one service becomes many. The Spring Cloud umbrella, which sub projects are still relevant in twenty twenty six, and which ones have been deprecated and replaced. Centralised configuration with Spring Cloud Config Server and its client side. Service discovery with Eureka, including why discovery matters and how it works. Application programming interface gateway with Spring Cloud Gateway, including routes, predicates, filters, and rate limiting. Circuit breakers with Resilience four j, including the at sign Circuit Breaker, at sign Retry, and at sign Time Limiter annotations, plus fallback methods. Distributed tracing with Micrometer Tracing and OpenTelemetry, with the trace context propagated across every hop. Spring Cloud Stream, the binder abstraction that decouples your messaging code from whichever broker is actually behind it. And the overlap between Spring Cloud and the underlying container platform, especially Kubernetes, so you know which Spring Cloud pieces to keep and which to let the platform handle. And finally a wrap up of the whole track.

Let us start with why Spring Cloud exists at all. A single Spring Boot service runs on one machine, reads its configuration from one file, talks directly to its database, and is one hypertext transfer protocol hop from its caller. The moment you split that single service into many, say payments, orders, fulfilment, users, and notifications, every assumption breaks.

Where is each service. The host names drift over time. Instances scale up and down constantly. A static load balancer in the middle is fragile. Where does configuration live. Editing one y a m l file in one repository does not work when thirty services need consistent feature flags and database connection strings. What happens when one service is slow. Without protection, slow callees can cascade, with threads piling up in every upstream service, until the whole system falls over together. Why is this request slow. It crossed five services. Logs in each service are isolated from each other. There is no obvious way to see where the time went. How does the message bus stay portable. The producer code should not need to know whether Kafka or RabbitMQ is actually behind it. Otherwise switching brokers is a rewrite.

Spring Cloud is an umbrella of projects that solve these distributed system problems with the same idiomatic Spring Boot patterns you already know. You add a starter dependency, you configure a few properties, you annotate a few classes. That is the developer experience. The same pattern as every other Spring extension.

Now, a quick tour of what is in the Spring Cloud umbrella, and what to skip. Spring Cloud has accreted a lot over the years. Some projects are essential. Some are legacy. And some have been superseded by platform level tools like Kubernetes and Istio. The projects worth your attention in twenty twenty six are the following.

Spring Cloud Config externalises configuration to a central server. Core. Spring Cloud Netflix Eureka is the service discovery registry. Core for virtual machine deployments. Optional on Kubernetes. Spring Cloud Gateway is the edge or application programming interface gateway. Core. Spring Cloud Circuit Breaker wraps Resilience four j and a few other libraries. Core. Spring Cloud Stream is the broker agnostic messaging abstraction. Core if you want portability across brokers.

A few projects you should know are deprecated. Spring Cloud Sleuth, which was the older distributed tracing library, has been replaced by Micrometer Tracing, which is built into the Spring Framework itself. Spring Cloud Hystrix, which was the older Netflix circuit breaker, has been replaced by Resilience four j. Spring Cloud Ribbon, which was the older client side load balancer, has been replaced by Spring Cloud Load Balancer. The deprecated names still live in old code bases, so it is worth recognising them. Do not start anything new with them.

There is also Spring Cloud Open Feign, which is a declarative hypertext transfer protocol client library. It is optional in modern code, because the Rest Client we introduced in notebook nine is fine for most needs. Use Open Feign if you have a strong taste for declarative clients. Use Rest Client otherwise.

The first core piece is centralised configuration with Spring Cloud Config. The config server is a small Spring Boot application that serves configuration to other services. The configurations themselves live in a Git repository. Versioned. Code reviewed. Audited. Each client service asks the config server for its own configuration at startup, and optionally subscribes to refresh events to pick up changes later without a restart.

The server is just a Boot application with one extra annotation, at sign Enable Config Server. In its application y a m l, you point it at a Git repository url and a default branch. That is all.

On the client side, each service uses its application name to identify itself. The bootstrap configuration imports config server, pointing at the server's url. Spring layers the response from the config server into the existing property source chain we covered in notebook eleven, at high precedence. So properties from the config server override the local application y a m l, but environment variables and command line flags can still override the config server.

For refresh without restart, you annotate beans that need to re bind their configuration with at sign Refresh Scope. Then a post request to slash actuator slash refresh on the client rebuilds those beans with the new values. For broadcasting refreshes to many instances at once, wire up Spring Cloud Bus, which uses Kafka or RabbitMQ as the transport, and a single post to one instance fans out to all of them.

The pattern is this. Configuration is code. Commit it. Review it. Deploy it through the same pipeline as your services. The config server is just a glorified Git client with a Spring shaped delivery surface.

Next, service discovery with Eureka. When payment service needs to call order service, it should not have to know the internet protocol address, the port, or even how many instances exist. A service registry solves this. Every service registers itself on startup. Callers query the registry by service name. The registry returns the current set of healthy instances.

Eureka is the registry from the Netflix open source stack that Spring Cloud has wrapped since the early days. Eureka is a tiny Boot application that maintains an in memory table mapping each service name to a list of instance urls. The table is updated by heartbeats from each registered service.

The Eureka server is a Boot application with at sign Enable Eureka Server. A single node configuration is two or three properties.

A client service registers itself by adding the Eureka client starter and pointing at the Eureka server url. Then in code, when you build a Rest Client to call another service, you use the logical service name as the host. So you write base url equals http colon slash slash order dash s v c, not the actual host of any specific instance. Spring Cloud Load Balancer resolves order dash s v c to a live instance at call time, picking from the set the registry knows about, with built in retries and load balancing.

On Kubernetes, service discovery is built into the platform. The url http colon slash slash order dash s v c resolves via the cluster's domain name system to the cluster internet protocol of the order dash s v c Kubernetes Service resource. Eureka becomes optional, and often redundant. Run Eureka when you are on plain virtual machines, Docker Swarm, or a hybrid cloud where domain name system based discovery is not enough. Skip Eureka on Kubernetes unless you have a specific reason to use it.

The next core piece is the application programming interface gateway. Spring Cloud Gateway is a non blocking edge gateway. It sits in front of all your microservices and handles cross cutting concerns that do not belong in every individual service. Routing requests to the right back end. Authentication and authorisation at the edge. Rate limiting. Request and response rewriting. Cross origin resource sharing. Retries. Header injection.

The gateway has two ideas. Predicates and filters. A predicate decides whether a given request matches a route. Common predicates match on path, on h t t p method, on header presence, on host, or on query parameter. A filter does something before forwarding the request or after receiving the response. Common built in filters include Add Request Header to inject metadata. Rewrite Path to strip or change path prefixes. Request Rate Limiter to enforce token bucket rate limits, backed by Redis. Circuit Breaker to wrap the downstream call in Resilience four j. Retry to retry on configured statuses. And Token Relay to forward o auth two access tokens to downstream services.

You declare routes in the application y a m l, or programmatically with the fluent Route Locator application programming interface for dynamic routing. Custom filters are just Gateway Filter beans you write yourself.

The whole gateway is reactive, built on Project Reactor and Netty. Non blocking under the hood. You do not write reactive code unless you are authoring custom filters, so the typical developer experience feels like declarative configuration.

Now, circuit breakers with Resilience four j. When payment service calls pricing service, and pricing service starts timing out, every payment request stacks up waiting. Threads pile up. Eventually payment service itself falls over. The pattern that prevents this is the circuit breaker. Once the failure rate exceeds a threshold, the breaker opens and short circuits future calls instantly, giving the downstream system time to recover.

The breaker has three states. Closed means normal traffic flow, with calls passing through. Open means the breaker is tripped, and calls are rejected instantly without even attempting the downstream call. After a configured wait, the breaker moves to half open, where it allows a small number of probe calls to test whether the downstream has recovered. If the probes succeed, the breaker closes. If they fail, it goes back to open.

Resilience four j is the modern circuit breaker library that Spring Cloud recommends. It is lightweight, functional, integrates with Spring Boot via the spring cloud starter circuitbreaker resilience four j dependency, and provides four resilience primitives that compose together. Circuit Breaker. Retry. Time Limiter. And Bulkhead, which limits the number of concurrent calls.

The configuration is declarative, in application y a m l. You define named instances, one per downstream dependency. Each instance has its own thresholds. Sliding window size for the failure rate calculation. Failure rate threshold for tripping. Wait duration in the open state. Permitted number of calls in half open.

In code, you annotate the gateway method with at sign Circuit Breaker, at sign Retry, and at sign Time Limiter, each naming the instance configuration to use. You also provide a fallback method, named in the fallbackMethod attribute, which is called when the circuit is open or when calls fail through the protections. The fallback method has the same signature as the protected method, plus an extra Throwable parameter that holds the failure cause. Inside the fallback, you return something sensible. A cached value. A default. A degraded mode response.

The pattern is this. Wrap every cross service call in a circuit breaker. Provide a fallback that returns something useful. Your service stays up when its dependencies do not. Resilience four j exports rich metrics through Micrometer, so you can dashboard breaker state, success rates, and call durations alongside your normal hypertext transfer protocol metrics.

Now, distributed tracing. A request that crosses five services produces logs in five different places. Without correlation, debugging a slow request means digging through five log files and trying to line up timestamps. Distributed tracing stitches the hops together by propagating a trace context. A trace identifier plus per hop span identifiers, threaded through every call.

Modern Spring uses Micrometer Tracing as the facade, replacing the deprecated Spring Cloud Sleuth. The backend implementation is either OpenTelemetry, which is the open standard with broad ecosystem support, or Zipkin Brave, which is the older but still maintained alternative. Plug Micrometer Tracing in once at the application level, and traces flow through every Rest Client call, every Web Client call, every Kafka Template send, every j d b c query, and every at sign Kafka Listener invocation automatically. The instrumentation is implicit.

You add two dependencies. The micrometer tracing bridge otel jar, which adapts Micrometer to OpenTelemetry. And the OpenTelemetry o t l p exporter, which sends the spans over the OpenTelemetry line protocol to an OpenTelemetry collector or directly to a back end that speaks the protocol.

In application y a m l, you set the tracing sampling probability. One hundred percent in development. Five to ten percent in production, to control trace volume costs. You set the o t l p endpoint url for where to send the spans. And critically, you update the logging pattern to include the trace identifier and span identifier in every log line, using the mapped diagnostic context placeholders for X traceId and X spanId.

With the bridge in place and the pattern updated, every log line includes the trace identifier. Every outgoing call propagates the world wide web consortium traceparent header, or alternatively the older b three headers, configurable. And your back end of choice, whether Tempo, Jaeger, Honeycomb, or Datadog, shows the full request waterfall from gateway to deepest downstream call.

You almost never write tracing code by hand. The instrumentation is automatic. When you do want to add a custom span around a slow internal computation, use the Micrometer Observation application programming interface, or use the at sign New Span annotation from the micrometer tracing annotation library.

Now, Spring Cloud Stream. Notebook eleven covered spring kafka directly. That works, but it ties your producer and consumer code to Kafka specifically. If you ever switch to RabbitMQ, or want to run the same code on a mock broker in tests, you have to rewrite everything.

Spring Cloud Stream is a higher level abstraction over messaging. You write messaging logic as plain java util function types. Supplier for producers. Function for transformers. Consumer for sinks. A binder plugs those functions into the actual broker. Swap binders by swapping a dependency. The business code does not change.

A Supplier of an event type becomes a producer. Each emission publishes to the output binding. A Consumer of an event type becomes a sink. It is invoked once per inbound message. A Function from one event type to another becomes a stream processor. It reads from one binding and writes its return value to another.

You bind function names to broker destinations in application y a m l. Each function has a naming convention. The function name, followed by dash out dash zero for the output binding, or dash in dash zero for the input binding. So order Producer dash out dash zero binds the producer's output to a topic called orders. Order Sink dash in dash zero binds the sink's input to the orders topic, with a consumer group name.

The binder is selected by adding the right dependency. Spring cloud stream binder kafka for Kafka. Spring cloud stream binder rabbit for RabbitMQ. Plus binders for Amazon Kinesis, Google Cloud Pub Sub, and several others. Configuration for the binder itself goes under spring cloud stream and the binder name.

The trade off is this. You get portability across brokers. You get a consistent programming model. You get a clean test story, because you can use the test binder, which requires no actual broker. You give up direct access to broker specific features. Kafka's transactions. RabbitMQ's headers exchange routing. When you need those, you can break out to the native application programming interface. For new code, Cloud Stream is the cleaner shape. For existing spring kafka code bases, the cost of migration usually is not worth it.

Finally, the overlap with the underlying container platform. A lot of what early Spring Cloud built, things like service discovery, configuration distribution, secret rotation, and network level load balancing, now ship inside the container platform itself. On Kubernetes, service discovery is built into the Service resource via domain name system. Configuration distribution is handled by Config Maps and Secrets, mounted as files or environment variables. Load balancing is handled by kube proxy and the Service abstraction. Mutual transport layer security and traffic shaping is handled by service meshes like Istio or Linkerd.

What Spring Cloud still owns at the application layer is the following. Spring Cloud Gateway gives you application aware routing, including JSON web token handling and o auth two token relay, which a layer four network gateway cannot do. Resilience four j gives you in process circuit breakers, retries, time limits, and bulkheads, which are different from the network level retries a service mesh provides. Micrometer Tracing gives you in process trace context propagation through your application's own internal code, not just across network boundaries. Spring Cloud Stream gives you the broker agnostic messaging abstraction. And Spring Cloud Config gives you application level configuration with rich refresh semantics, which Config Maps do not.

The pragmatic answer is this. Lean on Kubernetes for infrastructure level concerns. Use Spring Cloud for the patterns that belong inside the application itself. The two layers are complementary, not redundant.

That wraps notebook twelve, and it wraps the entire Java and Spring track. You have walked the full path. Notebooks one through seven covered modern Java, from var and records to virtual threads, ending with the java virtual machine internals and the annotation plus reflection mechanics that Spring is built on. Notebook eight covered Spring Core. The inversion of control container, dependency injection, aspect oriented programming, and the application context. Notebook nine covered Spring Web. Rest controllers, validation, error handling, and the essentials of Spring Security. Notebook ten covered Spring Data. J p a entity mapping, repositories, transactions, and database migrations. Notebook eleven covered Spring Boot in production. Auto configuration, externalised configuration, the actuator, the test slices, Testcontainers, Kafka messaging, and containerised deployment. Notebook twelve, this one, covered Spring Cloud. The config server, service discovery, the gateway, circuit breakers, distributed tracing, and broker agnostic messaging.

You can now build, test, observe, and operate a production Spring service. You can connect many of them together into a coherent distributed system.

Where to go from here. The Java foundation generalises. The java util function package, the Stream application programming interface, virtual threads, and the java virtual machine tooling are the same wherever you go on the java virtual machine, including Kotlin, Scala, and Clojure. The Spring patterns generalise too. Dependency injection. At sign Transactional. The aspect oriented programming proxy mechanism. Conditional auto configuration. The convention over configuration philosophy. All of these show up across every Spring shaped library, including Spring Batch for scheduled batch processing, Spring Integration for enterprise integration patterns, Spring Statemachine for state machines, and Spring AI for large language model integration. The mental model you built across these twelve notebooks is portable to all of them.

Welcome to working Java and Spring. Build something real.
